\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b cuneifolia} ({\i C. oviceps }Bornm.): Stems branched at the middle. Leaves white-tomentose, sometimes glabrescent; lower lyrate-pinnatifid. Involucre 12-14 × 7-8 mm; appendages brown, not spinose at apex.{\i  Stony hillsides. • Bulgaria, N. Greece, Turkey-in-Europe}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b pallida} (Friv.) Hayek, {\i Prodr. Fl. Penins. Balcan.}{\b  2}: 763 (1931): Stems branched at the middle. Leaves scabrid, appressed-white-tomentose, sometimes glabrescent; lower lyrate. Involucre 10-12 × 6-7 mm; appendages pale brown, with an apical spine c. 2·5 mm. •{\i  From N. & E. Greece to E. Romania}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b c}) Subsp. {\b sublanata} (DC.) Hayek,{\i  loc. cit. }(1931): Stems simple or branched at the base. Leaves arachnoid-lanate, sometimes glabrescent; lower lyrate. Involucre 12-14 × 7-8 mm; appendages black, the apex shortly spinose. {\i Throughout the range of the species except Romania, but in some regions only casual}.
\par

